Reasoning: The paper deals with the modification of a model of computation and the study of the class of problems that can be solved in polynomial time in this new model. This falls under the area of computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of semialgebraic functions and the study of their properties suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the areas of data structures (cs.DS) and logic in computer science (cs.LO). The study of continuous functions and the ability to compute arbitrarily small numbers may also be relevant to the area of scientific computing (cs.SC). Finally, the mention of a dichotomy in the class of problems that can be solved suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the area of neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE).
